# iot-smsctld — authenticated device control over SMS.
#
# The daemon consumes the MT-SMS envelope cellular-client publishes and answers
# with a single MO SMS. It is INERT until smsctl.enabled=true.
#
# Behaviour is driven by ds keys, not by this file — they hot-apply on change:
#
#   ds-cli set smsctl.enabled true
#   ds-cli set smsctl.allowed.numbers '"+919096383701,+4915112345678"'
#   ds-cli set smsctl.session.ttl.sec 600
#
# Command grammar (text these to the device's SIM number):
#
#   IOT LOGIN <user> <password>      # required first; users are the device-ui users
#   IOT STATUS                       # reg/signal/ip/vpn/wifi summary
#   IOT WIFI "<ssid>" "<psk>"        # set/replace the WiFi network + reconnect
#   IOT APN <apn>                    # set the data APN + cycle the radio
#   IOT RADIO RESTART                # CFUN 0/1 — recovers a CS-domain wedge
#   IOT REBOOT
#   IOT FACTORY-RESET                # replies with a 6-digit code…
#   IOT FACTORY-RESET <code>         # …which confirms the wipe
#   IOT LOGOUT
#
# SECURITY: the login password necessarily crosses the carrier in PLAINTEXT.
# Prefer a dedicated Admin account for SMS over the shared `admin` one, and set
# smsctl.allowed.numbers so unknown senders are dropped without a reply.
#
# Args are optional; the ds keys are the real control surface.
#   --ds-sock=PATH   ds-server unix socket (default: built-in)
IOT_SMSCTL_ARGS=""
